    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/zw18i.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 1663234,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1531124,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1531124/ghostcat",
                "reputation": 140819,
                "display_name": "GhostCat",
                "accept_rate": 96
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 3,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1758185384,
            "creation_date": 1539676031,
            "body": "<p>Previously, the simply answer was: there is <strong>no<\/strong> switching on &quot;type&quot; in Java. In contrast to languages such as Scala, Java doesn't have an almost magic &quot;pattern matching&quot; feature.<\/p>\n<p>Java 21 introduced such capabilities though. So the following information is only relevant when you are using a version of Java that is older than Java 21.<\/p>\n<p>When you really need to do that: figure the specific type of an Object instance, to then do different things based on the true nature of the object, such an if/else cascade is one of few choices.<\/p>\n<p>One alternative is to use a map, like <code>Map&lt;Class&lt;?&gt;, Consumer&lt;?&gt;)<\/code> or something alike. In other words: you (upfront) create a map that knows a <strong>method<\/strong> to call for different classes, and then do <code>obj.getClass()<\/code> to see if your map knows about that class. But that mechanism isn't very robust, as it only uses <code>equals()<\/code> for the class instances.<\/p>\n<p>Beyond that: there are only very few selected use cases where such kind of &quot;type switching&quot; makes sense. Typically, you approach this problem ... by stepping back, looking at the <em>real<\/em> underlying problem and designing a completely different solution.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 52830394,
            "question_id": 52830106,
            "last_edit_date": 1758185384
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/188f8f99306965f5d9b7afd57998ccc1?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 26075668,
                "user_type": "unregistered",
                "user_id": 19774655,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/19774655/michal",
                "reputation": 39,
                "display_name": "Michal"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 3,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1660642853,
            "creation_date": 1660642853,
            "body": "<p>It is possible as of <a href=\"https://blogs.oracle.com/javamagazine/post/java-pattern-matching-switch-preview\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Java 16 pattern matching for switch<\/a><\/p>\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>static String formatterPatternSwitch(Object o) {\n    return switch (o) {\n        case Integer i -&gt; String.format(&quot;int %d&quot;, i);\n        case Long l    -&gt; String.format(&quot;long %d&quot;, l);\n        case Double d  -&gt; String.format(&quot;double %f&quot;, d);\n        case String s  -&gt; String.format(&quot;String %s&quot;, s);\n        default        -&gt; o.toString();\n    };\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 73371926,
            "question_id": 52830106
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://graph.facebook.com/847798571930087/picture?type=large",
                "account_id": 5870718,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 4623129,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4623129/syed-khalid-ahmed",
                "reputation": 3242,
                "display_name": "Syed Khalid Ahmed"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1539675754,
            "creation_date": 1539675741,
            "body": "<p>You can check in this way:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public void put(Object obj) {\n    if (obj instanceof Integer) {\n\n    } else if (obj instanceof String) {\n\n    } else if (obj instanceof Boolean) {\n\n    } else if (obj instanceof List) {\n      List list = (List) obj;\n      if(!list.isEmpty()){\n        if(list.get(0) instanceof  String){\n          List&lt;String&gt; listString=(List&lt;String&gt;)obj;\n          //Do what  you want to do\n        }\n      }\n\n    } else if (obj instanceof Map) {\n      Map map = (Map) obj;\n      if(!map.isEmpty()){\n        Map.Entry entry = (Entry) map.entrySet().iterator().next();\n        if(entry.getKey() instanceof String &amp;&amp; entry.getValue() instanceof String){\n          Map&lt;String,String&gt; mapStrind= (Map&lt;String,String&gt;)obj;\n          //Do what  you want to do\n        }\n      }\n\n    }\n  }\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 52830306,
            "question_id": 52830106,
            "last_edit_date": 1539675754
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/YFMQM.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 12203943,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 8907549,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/8907549/melanzane",
                "reputation": 543,
                "display_name": "melanzane"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1539675333,
            "creation_date": 1539675155,
            "body": "<p>Use <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/10/docs/api/java/lang/Object.html#getClass%28%29\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><code>Object.getClass()<\/code><\/a>. It returns the runtime type of the object.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 52830146,
            "question_id": 52830106,
            "last_edit_date": 1539675333
        }
    ],
